### Armstrong Siddeley

[Armstrong Siddeley](/Armstrong_Siddeley) was a formidable British engineering company, formed by the acquisition of [Siddeley-Deasy](/Siddeley-Deasy) in 1919. They became renowned for producing a wide range of innovative piston, turboprop, turbojet, and rocket engines, often characterized by their distinctive radial designs and animal-themed names.

An [Armstrong Siddeley Tiger](/Science_Museum_(London)) engine, a powerful 14-cylinder radial, on display at the [London Science Museum](/Science_Museum_(London)).

Their impressive array of piston engines [3] included:

*   The [Armstrong Siddeley Terrier](/Armstrong_Siddeley_Terrier)
*   The [Armstrong Siddeley Mastiff](/Armstrong_Siddeley_Mastiff)
*   The [Armstrong Siddeley Boarhound](/Armstrong_Siddeley_Boarhound)
*   The highly successful [Armstrong Siddeley Cheetah](/Armstrong_Siddeley_Cheetah), a seven-cylinder radial that powered numerous British trainers and light transport aircraft.
*   The [Armstrong Siddeley Civet](/Armstrong_Siddeley_Civet)
*   The [Armstrong Siddeley Cougar](/Armstrong_Siddeley_Cougar)
*   The impressive [Armstrong Siddeley Deerhound](/Armstrong_Siddeley_Deerhound), a 21-cylinder, three-row radial engine, a true behemoth of power.
*   The [Armstrong Siddeley Genet](/Armstrong_Siddeley_Genet), a small, five-cylinder radial engine.
*   The [Armstrong Siddeley Genet Major](/Armstrong_Siddeley_Genet_Major), an uprated version of the Genet.
*   The [Armstrong Siddeley Hyena](/Armstrong_Siddeley_Hyena), an ambitious 15-cylinder radial.
*   The [Armstrong Siddeley Jaguar](/Armstrong_Siddeley_Jaguar), a 14-cylinder two-row radial.
*   The [Armstrong Siddeley Leopard](/Armstrong_Siddeley_Leopard), a large 14-cylinder radial.
*   The [Armstrong Siddeley Lynx](/Armstrong_Siddeley_Lynx), a seven-cylinder radial engine.
*   The [Armstrong Siddeley Mongoose](/Armstrong_Siddeley_Mongoose), a five-cylinder radial.
*   The [Armstrong Siddeley Ounce](/Armstrong_Siddeley_Ounce)
*   The [Armstrong Siddeley Panther](/Armstrong_Siddeley_Panther), a 14-cylinder two-row radial.
*   The [Armstrong Siddeley Puma](/Armstrong_Siddeley_Puma), originally developed by Siddeley-Deasy, a six-cylinder inline engine.
*   The [Armstrong Siddeley Serval](/Armstrong_Siddeley_Serval), a 10-cylinder two-row radial.
*   The [Armstrong Siddeley Tiger](/Armstrong_Siddeley_Tiger), a powerful 14-cylinder two-row radial.
*   Armstrong Siddeley Wolfhound – a paper project, indicating a planned, but never realized, development of the Deerhound.

Their venture into gas turbines showcased their adaptability to new propulsion technologies:

*   The [Armstrong Siddeley Adder](/Armstrong_Siddeley_Adder), an early turbojet.
*   The [Armstrong Siddeley ASX](/Armstrong_Siddeley_ASX), an experimental axial-flow turbojet.
*   The [Armstrong Siddeley Double Mamba](/Armstrong_Siddeley_Double_Mamba), a unique turboprop that coupled two Mamba engines, allowing one to be shut down in flight for fuel economy.
*   The [Armstrong Siddeley Mamba](/Armstrong_Siddeley_Mamba), a pioneering turboprop engine.
*   The [Armstrong Siddeley Python](/Armstrong_Siddeley_Python), a larger turboprop engine.
*   The powerful [Armstrong Siddeley Sapphire](/Armstrong_Siddeley_Sapphire), a highly successful axial-flow turbojet that powered many British and American aircraft.
*   The [Armstrong Siddeley Viper](/Armstrong_Siddeley_Viper), a compact turbojet engine, widely used in trainers and light attack aircraft.

Their bold exploration of rocket engines [14] was equally impressive:

*   Armstrong Siddeley Alpha
*   The [Armstrong Siddeley Beta](/Armstrong_Siddeley_Beta)
*   Armstrong Siddeley Delta
*   The [Armstrong Siddeley Gamma](/Bristol_Siddeley_Gamma), a liquid-propellant rocket engine used in the Black Knight research rocket.
*   The [Armstrong Siddeley Screamer](/Armstrong_Siddeley_Screamer), an early liquid-propellant rocket engine designed for interceptors.
*   The [Armstrong Siddeley Snarler](/Armstrong_Siddeley_Snarler), another early liquid-propellant rocket engine.
*   Armstrong Siddeley Spartan
*   The [Armstrong Siddeley Stentor](/Armstrong_Siddeley_Stentor), a liquid-propellant rocket engine for the Blue Steel stand-off missile.

Armstrong Siddeley's legacy is one of remarkable engineering diversity, from multi-cylinder piston engines to cutting-edge jet and rocket propulsion, contributing profoundly to British aerospace.

