### Austro-Daimler

Main article: [Austro-Daimler](/Austro-Daimler)

Source: Gunston [14]

[Austro-Daimler](/Austro-Daimler), the Austrian branch of the Daimler automotive empire, became a critical supplier of aircraft engines to the Austro-Hungarian air forces during World War I. Their inline-six engines were known for their robust construction and reliability, powering many of the Central Powers' aircraft.

Their extensive and influential engine lineup included:

*   The Austro-Daimler 35-40 hp 4-cylinder engine, with 100 mm × 120 mm (3.94 in × 4.72 in) cylinders [2] [4]. A foundational four-cylinder.
*   The Austro-Daimler 65-70 hp 4-cylinder, with 120 mm × 140 mm (4.72 in × 5.51 in) cylinders [2] [4].
*   The [Austro-Daimler 90hp 6-cylinder](/Austro-Daimler_90hp_6-cyl.), a significant inline-six with 120 mm × 140 mm (4.72 in × 5.51 in) cylinders [2]. This was a widely used engine.
*   The [Austro-Daimler 120hp 6-cylinder](/Austro-Daimler_120hp_6-cyl.), offering more power with 130 mm × 175 mm (5.12 in × 6.89 in) cylinders [2] [4].
*   The [Austro-Daimler 160hp 6-cylinder](/Austro-Daimler_160hp_6-cyl.).
*   The [Austro-Daimler 185hp 6-cylinder](/Austro-Daimler_185hp_6-cyl.).
*   The [Austro-Daimler 200hp 6-cylinder](/Austro-Daimler_200hp_6-cyl.), a powerful inline-six with 135 mm × 175 mm (5.31 in × 6.89 in) cylinders [2] [11].
*   The [Austro-Daimler 210hp 6-cylinder](/Austro-Daimler_210hp_6-cyl.).
*   The [Austro-Daimler 225hp 6-cylinder](/Austro-Daimler_225hp_6-cyl.).
*   The Austro-Daimler 300 hp V-12. A more complex and powerful V-engine.
*   The Austro-Daimler 360 hp 6-cylinder, a very high-output inline-six with 130 mm × 175 mm (5.12 in × 6.89 in) cylinders [2].
*   The Austro-Daimler 400 hp V-12, a powerful V-engine with 130 mm × 175 mm (5.12 in × 6.89 in) cylinders [2].
*   The Austro-Daimler D-35, another 400 hp V-12 with 130 mm × 175 mm (5.12 in × 6.89 in) cylinders [2].

Austro-Daimler's engines were pivotal in World War I, demonstrating the effectiveness of robust, liquid-cooled inline designs for military aviation.

